description.plain:
“Winter Takes All” is the first part of RA Scion’s two-part reflection on tests of faith and suicide.  Part one begins with the story of a tremendously spiritual man who has hit rock bottom.  Seeking answers, he looks back over his life and the path that lead him to his present state, and overwrought with depression, he contemplates suicide.

At the end of “Winter Takes All” the narrator ultimately decides to commit suicide and jumps;
 part two of the story is depicted in “Escaping Arkham,” which picks up exactly where “Winter Takes All” has left off, at the moment just after the narrator jumps.  In an interview with Seeds Entertainment, RA Scion explained:

At the end of “Winter Takes All” the protagonist jumps of the bridge. So that’s how the two songs are tied together. At the end of “Winter Takes All” the main character has battled all these things in the past and he finally resigned himself to freeing himself until he jumps and then “Escaping Arkham” is about the moment between the physical jump and death.

songs.title: Escaping Arkham

description.plain:
“Escaping Arkham” is the conclusion of RA Scion’s two-part reflection on tests of faith and suicide.  Part one is revealed in “Winter Takes All,” which tells the story of a man of faith battling depression who contemplates suicide and ultimately takes his own life by jumping from a bridge.  “Escaping Arkham” picks up where “Winter Takes All” leaves off, at the exact moment the man jumps.  In an interview with Seeds Entertainment, RA Scion explained that:

At the end of “Winter Takes All” the main character has battled all these things in the past and he finally resigned himself to freeing himself until he jumps and then “Escaping Arkham” is about the moment between the physical jump and death. The whole second verse talks about levitating and hovering, it’s actually describing when the subject jumps off of the bridge.

songs.title: Trouble Is

description.plain:
On the surface “Trouble Is” tells a tale about a vagrant farmer being accused of sketchy behavior by a community that ultimately takes his land and exiles him over a coin toss.  The story is an allegorical representation of RA Scion’s experience in the Seattle rap scene.  In an interview with The Find RA explained:

“Trouble Is” was intentionally written to be vague and esoteric. I wanted to tell of my limited experience with the Seattle hiphop community between 2001 and 2007 without having it sound like a journal entry, so I made up a fable, complete with a moralistic ending. The success of the tale literally revolves around the coin toss, and I don’t think I did a very good job of illustrating the farmer’s sacrifice for the benefit of the community.

description.plain:
One of the latest tracks from RA Scion and Sabzi, ‘Turn! Turn! Turn!’ is a thoughtful reflection about how the members of Common Market are aging to find that the things that they ran away from are, in fact, what they perhaps should have been doing all along.

The title itself references Ecclesiastes 3:1-8, which was famously referenced by The Byrds and Pete Seeger in their protest song, “Turn! Turn! Turn!” The Bible passage focused on how the human condition is one defined by changing seasons of circumstance. Some days, you want to run, and other days, you have to stay put.

In this song, RA Scion meditates on perhaps returning to Common Market, out of an understanding that other people need his perspective to grow themselves.

songs.title: Gol’ Dust

description.plain: This is just an amazing flow. The theme is classic David and Goliath. The lyrics are layered and cryptic and admit of multiple associations. Youthful warrior instinct coming from a “bastard” with the blood but missing the birthright, he “soldiers” on in the cause of destruction of oppressive structures, heart pure and back bowed in effort and labor. Reminiscent of Rush themes. This song attracts and inspires me greatly and captures the best spirit of the youthful moral warrior on the side of the weak and keeping the self humble all the while. Great imagery. It has to be more than a bit analogous to my bio, fitting as my middle name “Fitzgerald” meaning “bastard son of royalty.” I don’t see this lyric as self-aggrandizing in any way–he throws his lot in with the people even while he is perfectly capable of solitary striving for long periods. The traces of bravado are put to good use and assistance is sought during weak moments. Just a gem of a song.
